This campaign has already prompted responses from:

-
A **global university rankings organization**, which has escalated
the issue internally,  

- Multiple **Canadian and U.S.
universities**, which are now **reassessing their academic
partnerships** with Dongguk in light of **Title IX risk
exposure**.

Under **Title IX**, U.S. institutions are
required to ensure that their exchange and study abroad programs **do
not place students — particularly women — into environments where
harassment is tolerated, concealed, or structurally enabled**.
Continuing or initiating partnerships with Dongguk could expose
sending institutions to reputational and legal liability.

We
respectfully ask that IES:

- Share this case with Title IX
offices and study abroad compliance teams across your U.S. university
network,

- Encourage a pause or reassessment of any active or
pending partnerships with Dongguk University,

- Consider joining
a coordinated inquiry into whether Dongguk meets the student safety
standards expected in U.S.-linked programs.

We are
available to provide full documentation, source material, and
additional reports if your team would like to conduct further risk
review. Thank you for your continued work supporting safe and
accountable international education.

